The Revival of the Great Leader
London — — The Battle of Waterloo has been over for two hundred years, and Napoleon's catastrophic defeat in that battle severely damaged France's self-respect, to the point that General de Gaulle omitted any mention of the battle when writing the history of the French military.
Nevertheless, if you accept "greatness" as a personal trait, both Napoleon and de Gaulle could be called among the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say there is no such thing as a "great leader."
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created the environment in which a "strange mediocrity" like Napoleon could become a hero.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not particularly outstanding as a general; his victories were due to the courage and devotion of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Regardless of whether Napoleon was great, we must determine whether it is possible to describe any leader as great.
If the answer is yes, then who can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believes that great leaders must meet two particularly important criteria.
First of all, can this leader recognize historical trends?
Otto von Bismarck did, and his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer; using Bismarck's memorable phrase, both heard the "rustle of God's cloak."
Secondly, did this leader make important decisions?
Of course, if a leader is forced to make decisions, he or she cannot be blamed for it nor take credit for it.
Therefore, the key lies in whether the leader had the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the right decisions on behalf of the nation.
De Gaulle should therefore be listed among any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the post-WWII decline.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country, crushing two failed coups, ending the Algerian War, and drafting the Constitution of the Fifth Republic.
Like British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview, establishing their place in the post-war global order.
In fact, the long-term impact of de Gaulle and Churchill in shaping their countries' worldviews was somewhat excessive.
Their successors for years afterward viewed the world — and France's role in it — through the lens of constrained rationality and distorted decision-making.
The result was that leaders of both countries after that were never able to achieve accomplishments that could match those of the two great leaders.
But there was also one British prime minister who could match them: she was Margaret Thatcher, a very controversial figure, loved by as many as she was disliked.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was due to resistance from her own cabinet and party.
It is not necessary to please everyone in order to become a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics could not deny her impact.
As the first female Prime Minister of the United Kingdom and almost certainly one of the earliest female Prime Ministers in other countries, Thatcher helped reverse Britain's economic decline.
Moreover, her attack on overly powerful trade unions enhanced the country's manageability during a time when it seemed to be slipping into chaos and disorder.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be considered a candidate for the title of "great leader."
Similarly, although far from flawless, Deng in China also has the qualifications to be considered a great leader.
Aside from assisting Mao in causing harm, Deng played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Square massacre.
But Deng also activated the market, leading China onto an unprecedented path of development and prosperity that ultimately enabled hundreds of millions of Chinese people to escape poverty.
Many people believe that Lee Kuan Yew, the founder and long-serving Prime Minister of Singapore, was very great, although he may have wished to showcase his talents on a larger stage.
In fact, the size of a country does not seem to affect a person's ability to become a great leader.
I said nothing derogatory when I mentioned that a country as small as Luxembourg was unlikely to produce a great leader, especially since the political atmosphere in the country is generally not controversial.
Canada's vast territory is sufficient to serve as a cradle for the birth of great leaders.
Some presidents also indeed achieved a great deal.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — — although not intellectual giants — — displayed remarkable judgment in establishing the postwar international order that supported world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, possessed extremely high talent — — the art of inspiring and persuading.
John F. Kennedy was skilled in both areas.
He accomplished a great task: defusing the Cuban Missile Crisis.
His ability to inspire was unmatched; in fact, his assassination solidified the tradition he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has yet been considered a great figure after Nelson Mandela's death, as Mandela embodied courage, authority, and graceful magnanimity.
In fact, he was the most charismatic and charming leader I have ever encountered; the other two — — former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former U.S. Secretary of State Colin Powell — — were either African or African American.
So what about today?
The only one qualified to claim greatness is the de facto leader of the EU, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at the beginning, but made few mistakes when making important decisions.
Kohl set generous terms for German unification; Merkel opposed Putin during his invasion of Ukraine and took a tolerant stance on the immigration crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy were wrong.
Political leaders — — the exercisers of political power — — can change the situation, for better or worse.
Merkel is the most obvious example today, as she pointed the way for Europe to deal with high-stakes survival crises.
